INSERT INTO fests VALUES (1,'Nortel Networks Palm Springs International Film Festival','Camelot Theatres','2300 E. Baristo Road','Palm Springs','92262','1-760-322-2930','1700 E. Tahquitz Canyon Way, Suite 3','','Palm Springs','CA','92262','1-760 322 2930','1-760 322 4087','info@psfilmfest.org','http://www.psfilmfest.org','http://www.psfilmfest.org/images/new/largelogo1.gif','http://www.psfilmfest.org/images/2003Feature%20Application.pdf','2002-11-01','2002-11-15','0000-00-00','2004-01-09','2004-01-19','Completed entry form<br />\r\nEntry fee<br />\r\n1/2&quot; VHS - NTSC or PAL format video<br />\r\nOne B&amp;W or Color Still (may e-mail a Jpeg  minimum of 300 dpi)<br />\r\n','Palm Springs International Film Festival is a unique organization - a non-profit entity with one staff operating two world-class international film events in the City of Palm Springs. As producer of both the Nortel Networks Palm Springs International Film Festival and the Palm Springs International Festival of Short Films, PSIFF is a recreational, educational and professional resource for more than 70,000 movie-lovers, entertainment industry executives and film-makers from Southern California and around the world each year.<br />\r\n<br />\r\nWhat began as one mayor&#039;s attempt to add vitality to his town has grown into &quot;one of the best showcases for international film,&quot; according to the LA Times. Routinely attended by film industry executives and filmmakers from across the globe, The Nortel Networks Palm Springs International Film Festival, held in January each year, boasts an attractive film sales and distribution record and is seen by American distributors as one of the best Academy Award campaign marketing tools. But easily the most exciting aspect of the festival is its enthusiastic, sophisticated audience. From age 5 to 85, men, women, children, local, international, this festival has become a &quot;people-friendly&quot; event, bringing together communities as diverse as the retired citizens of the desert and the young, hip industry crowd of Los Angeles.','','The festival features cultural events, filmmaker tributes, industry seminars and an annual black-tie gala award presentation. The festival screens a majority of the official international submissions to the Academy of Motion Picture Arts and Sciences for Best Foreign Language Film.','','USA','Western','',NULL,'North America',0,'',600,180,0,'Lifetime Achievement Award in Producing <br />\r\nLifetime Achievement Award in Directing<br />\r\nDaVinci Award for Achievement in Cinematography<br />\r\nFrederick Loewe Award for Career Achievement in Film Composing<br />\r\nDesert Palm Award for Career Achievement in Acting<br />\r\nJean Luis Award for Career Achievement in Costume Design<br />\r\nInternational Distributors Award<br />\r\nInternational Spotlight Award<br />\r\nInternational Filmmakers Awards<br />\r\nCareer Achievement Awards<br />\r\nInternational Federation of Film Critics (FIPRESCI) Prize',1,'There are nightly receptions, parties on the opening and closing nights, as well as a black-tie Gala Awards presentation and dinner dance ','Sparkles with thought-provoking, funny, insightful, entertaining film fare, events and explorations of the art of cinema.','The Festival is one of the largest film festivals in the country, screening over 180 films from more than 55 countries. The Festival screens a majority of the official international submissions to the Academy of Motion Picture Arts and Sciences for Best Foreign Language Film.','',1,'2003-07-23','CA');
INSERT INTO fests VALUES (3,'Solothurn Film Festival','Solothurner Filmtage','Postfach 1564','Solothurn','4502','41 32 625 80 80','Unt. Steingrubenstrasse 19,','PO Box 140','Solothurn','CH','4502','41 32 625 80 80','41 32 623 64 10','info@solothurnerfilmtage.ch','http://www.solothurnerfilmtage.ch','http://www.solothurnerfilmtage.ch/imgdb/128/018.jpg','http://www.solothurnerfilmtage.ch/download/','0000-00-00','2002-10-31','0000-00-00','2003-01-20','2003-01-25','','In 1966, with a low turnout rate and lack of means and educational opportunities for young and independent filmmaking in Switzerland, the stage was set for a meeting on &quot;Swiss film today&quot;. Its success called for a repeat; those who represented a new appreciation for film had found a platform for their films and film concerns in Solothurn. The initiator of the meeting, at that time called the &quot;Film-Gilde Solothurn&quot;, evolved into the &quot;Schweizerische Gesellschaft Solothurner Filmtage&quot;. Since that time, the occasion has been called the Solothurn Film Festival. In addition, the foundation for a Swiss Film Center was also established in Solothurn in 1967 and, since 1998, the awarding of the Swiss Film Prize has taken place at the Festival.\r<br />\n\r<br />\nThe Solothurn Film Festival has always been an integral part of the history of Swiss film and socio-political issues. While the program focuses on &#039;Works&#039; with current films and videos from all four linguistic regions, there are also &#039;Special Programs&#039; which deal with works from film schools and from abroad, television and co-productions, as well as a retrospective of a particular individual in film industry. In addition, various &#039;Events&#039;, which are associated with institutes and professional organisations, provide the opportunity for discussions concerning the politics of and pending issues in the world of film.','','','Over the course of the years, the Solothurn Film Festival has established itself as the most important meeting place for Swiss filmmakers, the media and the public. Contacts are made, opinions formed and the basis for new projects is laid here. The increasing number of box office admissions bear witness to continuing interest in &quot;internal affairs&quot;.			','Switzerland','','',NULL,'Europe',0,'',NULL,NULL,0,'The Solothurn Film Festival is a showing of works without competition. Information concerning the &#039;Prizes&#039; awarded at the Solothurn Film Festival can be found at our Web site. The Swiss Film Prize, which is awarded on the occasion of the Solothurn Film Festival, is a collective undertaking of the Federal Office for Culture, the Swiss Broadcasting Corporation (SRG SSR ide suisse), the Solothurn Film Festival, the Nyon Documentary Film Festival &quot;Visions du Rel&quot;, the Locarno International Film Festival, and the Swiss Film Center.\r<br />\n\r<br />\nThe Swiss Film Prize is a joint initiative of the Federal Office for Culture, the Swiss Broadcasting Corporation (SRG SSR ide suisse), the Solothurn Film Festival, the Nyon Documentary Film Festival &quot;Visions du Rel&quot;, the Locarno International Film Festival, and the Swiss Film Center. The prize was awarded for the first time in1998. Film nominations are submitted by the six sponsoring organisations, in collaboration with the Swiss Short Film Agency and Swissperform. A six-member jury selects the winners in the five categories. The prizes awarded in each of the categories include: \r<br />\n\r<br />\n&quot; Best Fiction Film &quot; (CHF 50&#039;000), \r<br />\n&quot; Best Documentary Film &quot; (CHF 50,000) and \r<br />\n&quot; Best Short Film &quot;(CHF 20,000), as well as \r<br />\n&quot;Best Actress&quot; (CHF 15,000) and the \r<br />\n&quot;Best Actor&quot; (CHF 15,000). \r<br />\n',2,'','The most important meeting place for Swiss filmmakers','','',1,'2002-12-20','');
