INSERT INTO fests VALUES (309,'Australian International Documentary Conference','','','Byron Bay','','','PO Box 157','','Lismore NSW','Australia','2480','+61 2 6620 3932','+61 2 6622 1954','aidc2004@aidc.com.au','http://www.aidc.on.net','http://www.aidc.com.au/images/main_nav_03.gif','','0000-00-00','2002-12-01','0000-00-00','2003-02-14','2003-02-23','','The AIDC is one of the largest recurrent screen industry conferences in Australia averaging between 500 to 800 national and international delegates. It provides a market place for documentary product for national and international buyers and distributors, showcases the work of Australian and international documentary makers, and creates a forum to discuss content, craft, technology and future directions.','','The market component of the Conference includes the Australian DocuMart (an all day pitching session for short-listed applicants), the ABC pitch&#039;n&#039; punt session, take a VIP to breakfast (or an alternative to breakfast take a VIP to morning golf - pitch and putt) and the hundreds of one-on-one informal pitches enabled by the AIDC - creators and decision-makers in conversation over a coffee or drink in the cafes and bars of Byron Bay. <br />\r\n<br />\r\n','','Australia','','',NULL,'Australia',0,'',0,0,0,'',0,'','Foster professional development for documentary content creators','AIDC 2003 is also a place for the big discussions about the future of Australian documentary. The current market demands are pushing makers to think outside the limits of conventional structures, lengths and devices. There is a debate about how a documentary &#039;industry&#039; can create popular television and at the same time find the space for diversity and landmark projects. And there is the continuing discussion of new models to put more money into the ever-threatened pot of documentary funding.','',1,'2003-07-24','');
