INSERT INTO fests VALUES (1408,'Amnesty International Film Festival','Kleine-Gartmanplantsoen 10','De Balie','Amsterdam','1017 RR','','PO box 1968','','Amsterdam','Netherlands','1000 BZ','+31 20 6263346','+31 20 6240889','filmfestival@amnesty.nl','http://www.amnesty.nl/filmfestival/index_en.html','http://www.amnesty.nl/filmfestival/img/logo_filmfestival.jpg','http://www.amnesty.nl/filmfestival/ff_entryform_en.html','0000-00-00','2003-12-01','0000-00-00','2003-03-20','2003-03-23','A short outline of the story in English, German, French or Dutch<br />\r\nAt least two different stills from the film (at least one black and white)<br />\r\nA list of credits<br />\r\nA short biography of the director(s)<br />\r\n<br />\r\n','The fifth Amnesty International Film Festival took place in Amsterdam from the 20th until the 23rd of March. For over forty years, Amnesty International has diligently been working at the observance of human rights worldwide. The written and spoken word in reports, letters to prisoners, governments en international organisations, political lobbys, speeches etc.  has proven to be a strong medium. Amnesty empathically can not and does not wish to neglect the global shift towards visual culture. The meaning of (film)images as a source of information increases. Visuals have proven they can break through indifference. In recent years numerous examples have shown how the camera has launched international action. Filming itself can also be considered a form of taking action. With small and advanced DV-cameras, it is becoming less difficult to inspect regimes anywhere in the world. ','','','Human Rights issues','Netherlands','','Films and videos are submitted complete with English commentary and/or English dialogue or in the original version with English subtitles. <br />\r\nVideos should be submitted for final screening at the festival on Betacam SP PAL. <br />\r\n',NULL,'Europe',0,'',200,40,0,'On the International Documentary Filmfestival Amsterdam (IDFA) and the International Film Festival Rotterdam (IFFR), Amnesty International and Foundation DOEN introduce a new film prize for films dealing with human rights issues. Ten films from each festival are nominated for the Amnesty International  DOEN Awards. The purpose of the introduction of the Amnesty International  DOEN Awards is to put these films in the spotlight, to expose them to a larger audience and to stimulate committed filmmakers. At the IDFA as well as on the IFFR, forum discussions will take place with reference to these Awards involving filmmakers, jury members, journalists, human right activists and the audience. This Award consist of a scholarship of  5000 and a small release of the film in the Netherlands. <br />\r\n',2,'','Movies that Matter - Bringing film to bear on human rights','The Amnesty International Film Festival presents all the films of the Amnesty International -DOEN selections of the IDFA and the IFFR, complemented by a number of other important films about human rights. The winners of this competition are shown in several cities during the Amnesty International Film Festival on Tour which will be held after the Amnesty International Film Festival in March 2003. ','',1,'2003-07-23','');
